# PDF to Slidev Presentation Workflow

When the user provides a PDF to convert into a new presentation, follow these steps in order.

## 1. Extract text with OCR

Run the existing OCR script against the provided PDF:

```bash
python3 ocr_extract.py "/path/to/file.pdf"
```

Prerequisites (install once if missing): `brew install tesseract tesseract-lang poppler` and `pip3 install pdf2image pytesseract Pillow`.

Read the output carefully — OCR is imperfect. Cross-reference with the original PDF (use the Read tool on the PDF) to fix garbled text, missing code blocks, and broken tables.

## 2. Create the presentation subdirectory

Choose a short, lowercase, English slug (e.g. `introduction`, `lambda-calculus`, `clojure`).

```
<slug>/
  package.json
  slides.md
  public/logos/   (if images are needed)
```

## 3. Create `package.json`

Use this template — only change the `name` and `build --base` path:

```json
{
  "name": "programacion-III-<slug>",
  "private": true,
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "slidev",
    "build": "slidev build --base /programacion-III-material/<slug>/",
    "export": "slidev export"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "@slidev/cli": "^52.14.1",
    "@slidev/theme-bricks": "^0.25.0"
  }
}
```

Then run `npm install` inside the new directory (with `ulimit -n 10240` on macOS).

## 4. Write `slides.md`

Use `theme: bricks` and follow the conventions from the existing `introduction/slides.md`:

- Frontmatter: theme, title, info, author, keywords, transition, mdc
- Use Slidev layouts: `center`, `default`, `two-cols`, `image-right`, etc.
- Code blocks: use Slidev syntax highlighting with line highlights `{all|1|2-4}`
- Use `<v-click>` for progressive reveal
- Use UnoCSS/Tailwind utility classes for layout (grid, flex, absolute positioning)
- Logos go in `public/logos/` — download from CDN (devicons, simpleicons) or create SVGs
- Language: Spanish (matching the original PDF content)

## 5. Download icons/logos

Use jsdelivr CDN for devicons:

```bash
curl -sL "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/devicons/devicon@latest/icons/<name>/<name>-original.svg" -o public/logos/<name>.svg
```

Verify each SVG is actual content (not a redirect/HTML page). If broken, create a minimal custom SVG.

## 6. Update root `index.html`

Add a new `<li>` entry inside `.card-list` with:
- Incremented card number
- `href="./slug/"` and `data-dev-port` matching the next available port (3031 + N)
- Title and short description

## 7. Test locally

```bash
cd <slug> && ulimit -n 10240 && npx slidev --port <port>
```

Or from the root: `npm run dev` (uses `dev.sh` which auto-discovers all presentations).

Verify every slide renders correctly. Check for broken images, OCR artifacts, and layout issues.

## 8. Commit and push (optional — only if user requests)

The user always reviews the generated presentation manually before committing. Only commit and push if explicitly asked.
